is perhaps the evil sibling of the story,

15:56.720 --> 15:58.000
if I can call it that.

15:58.000 --> 15:59.200
And that's metrics.

16:00.560 --> 16:02.000
So what do we mean by metric?

16:02.640 --> 16:03.520
What is a metric?

16:04.080 --> 16:06.000
A metric, one way to put it is a metric

16:06.000 --> 16:08.800
is a scoring system for reality, right?

16:08.800 --> 16:10.960
A game is a scoring system imposed

16:10.960 --> 16:13.200
on an artificial separate universe.

16:13.200 --> 16:15.920
It's this old idea that games happen in a magic circle

16:15.920 --> 16:18.080
and you go in and you try to, you know,

16:18.080 --> 16:20.000
destroy your spouse and then you step back and you're like,

16:20.000 --> 16:21.120
ah, everything's fine again.

16:22.000 --> 16:26.320
Metrics are what happens when you use quantitative data

16:27.280 --> 16:30.160
about the real world and you transform that

16:30.160 --> 16:31.920
into a target or a scoring system.

16:31.920 --> 16:34.880
It's when you target something that can be easily measured.

16:35.680 --> 16:36.640
In the game's half of the book,

16:36.640 --> 16:38.720
the core concept is striving play, which we've talked about.

16:39.520 --> 16:41.440
On the metric side, the core concept for me

16:41.440 --> 16:43.200
is the idea of value capture.

16:43.840 --> 16:49.200
Value capture is what happens when your values

16:49.200 --> 16:50.800
are kind of rich and subtle

16:51.360 --> 16:53.440
and then you enter an institution or a social setting

16:53.440 --> 16:54.720
that feeds you simplified,

16:54.720 --> 16:57.200
typically quantified renditions of those values

16:57.200 --> 16:58.880
and the simplified ones take over.

16:58.880 --> 17:02.640
So for me, it was going to philosophy graduate school

17:02.640 --> 17:04.000
out of a love of philosophy

17:04.000 --> 17:06.560
and then coming out obsessed with citation rates

17:06.560 --> 17:08.160
in highly ranked journals.

17:08.160 --> 17:09.680
For a lot of scientists I know,

17:09.680 --> 17:10.960
they go into the love of wisdom

17:10.960 --> 17:13.040
and they come out obsessed with like grant numbers

17:13.040 --> 17:14.880
and how big your grants are.

17:14.880 --> 17:17.440
For journalists, it becomes page views.

17:17.440 --> 17:19.040
For a lot of us on social media,

17:19.040 --> 17:21.440
you start wanting communication

17:21.440 --> 17:24.160
and you start ending up wanting likes.

17:24.160 --> 17:27.200
And so the important thing for me about a metric

17:27.200 --> 17:29.280
is that a metric presents you a target

17:29.280 --> 17:30.560
and a target that's limited

17:30.560 --> 17:32.160
in the way we talked about before.

17:32.160 --> 17:34.480
It's limited because of the need

17:34.480 --> 17:36.160
for everyone to count together.

17:36.160 --> 17:38.400
So it's limited to touching on the kind of features

17:38.400 --> 17:41.760
that everyone can count easily, height, number of flips.

17:41.760 --> 17:45.440
And then if what's actually valuable

17:46.160 --> 17:48.000
is not what's easily counted,

17:48.000 --> 17:52.800
then value capture will tend to push your values away

17:53.840 --> 17:55.280
from what actually matters.

17:55.280 --> 17:57.920
By the way, maybe this will entertain you.

