Exactly.

19:54.640 --> 19:56.880
And this is the part where I want to caution,

19:56.880 --> 19:57.520
and I want to be like,

19:57.520 --> 20:00.080
it's really easy to point at other people and laugh,

20:00.080 --> 20:02.400
but I think it's very easy

20:02.400 --> 20:05.280
to find value capture cases in your own life.

20:05.280 --> 20:08.480
I've been value captured by the quest for lower weight,

20:08.480 --> 20:11.760
the quest for optimizing my macronutrients,

20:11.760 --> 20:14.400
the quest to get higher on the philosophy rankings.

20:15.120 --> 20:17.600
Each of these things has for some period of time

20:17.600 --> 20:20.080
consumed me, and it's really wild

20:20.080 --> 20:23.200
because it's so miserable a lot of the times.

20:25.840 --> 20:27.600
The thing that I find really fascinating

20:27.600 --> 20:29.600
is how easy it is to lose your grip

20:29.600 --> 20:30.800
on what really matters

20:30.800 --> 20:33.200
when you're presented with a simple, clear number,

20:33.200 --> 20:34.720
both institutionally,

20:34.720 --> 20:36.800
like in my academic life,

20:36.800 --> 20:39.360
I'm in large-scale institutions that have,

20:39.360 --> 20:42.000
to my mind, stopped targeting things

20:42.000 --> 20:44.560
like teaching curiosity, teaching reflection,

20:44.560 --> 20:46.320
teaching any kind of intellectual virtue,

20:46.320 --> 20:47.520
and started targeting things

20:47.520 --> 20:50.080
like graduation rate and graduation speed.

20:50.080 --> 20:53.440
Again, easy measurables that capture people's attention

20:54.000 --> 20:57.120
because they are easy to express.

20:57.840 --> 21:00.240
Yeah, so I think you mentioned there

21:00.240 --> 21:03.040
one, as you say, slightly gross example,

21:03.040 --> 21:04.480
and then a more serious one,

21:04.480 --> 21:06.960
but the first thing that perhaps came to my mind

21:06.960 --> 21:08.160
when I was thinking about this

21:08.160 --> 21:10.720
is where the emphasis is placed

21:10.720 --> 21:12.880
on the incorrect metric

21:12.880 --> 21:14.720
would be something like GP appointments.

21:14.720 --> 21:16.320
Like there's a lot of talk about this

21:16.320 --> 21:17.840
at the moment over here in the UK,

21:18.560 --> 21:22.400
and you can reach a point where sort of GP practices,

21:22.400 --> 21:24.240
let's say hypothetically,

21:24.240 --> 21:26.720
we're rating these practices

21:26.720 --> 21:28.480
on the number of patients that they're seeing.

21:29.120 --> 21:30.640
So if we're concentrating on that,

21:30.640 --> 21:32.160
obviously what we're going to do

21:32.880 --> 21:34.480
is reduce the appointment time

21:34.480 --> 21:36.480
so we can fit in more appointments per day.

21:37.120 --> 21:40.160
And the only logical conclusion to that

21:40.720 --> 21:43.520
to me seems that the quality of care is going to go down.

21:44.080 --> 21:47.920
But if we're using this metric to rate them on,

21:47.920 --> 21:51.120
it will go up while the quality,

21:51.120 --> 21:52.320
the sort of rating goes up,

21:52.320 --> 21:54.320
while the quality of care goes down.

21:54.320 --> 21:58.000
So is that the kind of example that you're talking about?

21:58.000 --> 22:00.800
Right, that's exactly the kind of example I'm talking about.

22:00.800 --> 22:03.040
Actually, that example is a great one.

22:03.040 --> 22:04.400
I think whenever I talk about this stuff,

22:04.400 --> 22:05.120
everyone wants to tell me

22:05.120 --> 22:06.640
about the terrible metric in their life,

22:06.640 --> 22:09.120
but I think it's actually more unnerving

22:09.200 --> 22:11.040
for me to think about subtler examples.

22:11.040 --> 22:12.560
I think it's going to be really obvious.

22:13.280 --> 22:15.920
I mean, so I'm a professor.

22:15.920 --> 22:17.280
I'm rated on student evaluations.

22:17.280 --> 22:18.960
We all know the way to get high student evaluations

22:18.960 --> 22:20.560
is to make an easy class.

22:20.560 --> 22:21.840
Students don't learn as much,

22:21.840 --> 22:23.360
but you get higher evaluations.

22:23.920 --> 22:27.840
Lousy metrics are really, really obvious.

22:27.840 --> 22:30.960
I think some of the most nauseating cases for me

22:30.960 --> 22:32.720
are cases where the metrics are pretty good,

22:33.840 --> 22:34.960
but imperfect.

22:34.960 --> 22:37.200
And the one that this is perhaps

22:37.200 --> 22:39.200
a politically dangerous view,

22:39.200 --> 22:42.160
but a worrisome one for me that I've been obsessed with

22:42.160 --> 22:44.400
since the COVID pandemic is the degree

22:44.400 --> 22:46.960
to which easy public health metrics

22:46.960 --> 22:50.560
like lives saved and life expectancy

22:51.440 --> 22:53.840
tend to trump other considerations

22:53.840 --> 22:56.160
like life quality, cultural quality,

22:56.160 --> 22:57.840
community, mental health.

22:58.480 --> 23:02.160
And I'm not saying that it's not important to save lives,

23:02.960 --> 23:06.000
but I'm saying maybe a less controversial example for me

23:06.000 --> 23:09.200
is like saturated fats, like cheese, right?

23:09.200 --> 23:13.520
It's very easy to track heart attack rates,

23:13.520 --> 23:16.880
longer lifespans, very hard to track culinary joy.

23:17.440 --> 23:19.120
The claim here isn't anti-scientific.

23:19.120 --> 23:21.200
There is a genuine real correlation

23:21.200 --> 23:23.280
between saturated fats and heart attack rates.

23:23.280 --> 23:25.440
The claim is certain kinds of things

23:25.440 --> 23:28.080
that are easier to measure tend to beat out automatically

23:28.080 --> 23:30.960
and unthinkingly other harder to measure values.

23:31.680 --> 23:32.800
And try to understand this.

23:32.800 --> 23:35.280
So there's one common response here,

23:35.280 --> 23:36.800
which is, oh, that's just a bad metric.

23:36.800 --> 23:38.560
We need to find better metrics.

23:38.560 --> 23:40.320
And I had this gut, a lot of the time

23:40.320 --> 23:41.040
when I was thinking about this,

23:41.040 --> 23:43.840
I had this gut response that you wouldn't be able

23:43.840 --> 23:46.640
to find better metrics for certain kinds of things,

23:46.640 --> 23:48.480
especially central human values.

23:48.480 --> 23:49.760
And I was trying to understand why.

23:49.760 --> 23:51.520
And I found some answers,

23:51.520 --> 23:54.560
especially from some philosophers like Elizabeth Barnes

23:54.560 --> 23:56.000
who works on the notion of health

23:56.000 --> 23:57.440
and then a bunch of historians

23:57.440 --> 23:59.920
in a field called science and technology studies.

24:00.480 --> 24:02.960
So Theodore Porter unlocked a huge amount

24:02.960 --> 24:03.680
of this stuff for me.

24:03.680 --> 24:06.880
And this is a thing I am literally dying to talk about

24:06.880 --> 24:08.480
on the BBC science podcast.

24:08.480 --> 24:09.680
Because this, okay.

24:10.480 --> 24:12.480
So Theodore Porter was a historian

24:12.480 --> 24:14.880
who was inspired by actually by a bunch of philosophers

24:14.880 --> 24:17.520
I have to claim like Ian Hacking and Bruno Latour.

24:17.520 --> 24:21.360
And he was really interested in why politicians

24:21.360 --> 24:23.760
and administrators tended to unthinking

24:23.760 --> 24:27.440
kind of automatically reach for quantitative justification,

24:27.440 --> 24:29.040
even when the metrics were bad.

24:30.080 --> 24:32.640
So the theory he developed was that

24:32.640 --> 24:35.200
there were two kinds of ways of knowing about the world,

24:35.200 --> 24:36.640
qualitative and quantitative.

24:37.440 --> 24:39.920
And it's not that quantitative is bad.

24:39.920 --> 24:41.760
It's that each of them is a tool designed

24:41.760 --> 24:43.120
for a different purpose

24:43.120 --> 24:45.040
with different strengths and weaknesses.

24:45.040 --> 24:46.560
And the problem is compulsively reaching

24:46.560 --> 24:47.440
for the quantitative.

24:48.000 --> 24:51.200
So qualitative justification, written words,

24:51.200 --> 24:53.760
is open-ended, dynamic, subtle, rich,

24:53.760 --> 24:56.320
but it travels badly between contexts

24:56.320 --> 24:58.720
because it requires a huge amount of shared background.

24:59.600 --> 25:02.000
So one way for me, my example is as a professor,

25:02.000 --> 25:04.800
when I write qualitative evaluations of my students,

25:04.800 --> 25:06.960
I can respond along multiple dimensions.

25:06.960 --> 25:09.360
I don't have to declare a single overall score.

25:09.360 --> 25:10.640
I can be like, well, you're really creative,

25:10.640 --> 25:11.440
but it wasn't as rigorous.

25:11.440 --> 25:12.640
I didn't have to settle that up.

25:12.640 --> 25:14.880
And I can also use all the rich language,

25:14.880 --> 25:16.480
a philosophy of my class.

25:17.360 --> 25:20.480
But one, those things don't travel well.

25:20.480 --> 25:21.840
Like people from the business school

25:21.840 --> 25:22.960
will not understand my comments

25:22.960 --> 25:25.360
and I won't understand their student comments.

25:25.360 --> 25:27.280
And two, they do not aggregate well.

25:27.280 --> 25:31.040
Like thousands of student evaluations don't aggregate.

25:31.920 --> 25:36.720
So what Porter says is quantitative information

25:36.720 --> 25:38.880
is a kind of instrument that's designed

25:38.880 --> 25:40.640
to get around this problem.

25:40.640 --> 25:43.600
When we create quantitative information in an institution,

25:44.480 --> 25:47.440
we identify a context-invariant kernel.

25:47.440 --> 25:50.640
We find something that's stable across all contexts,

25:50.640 --> 25:53.360
that everyone from different backgrounds can understand.

25:53.360 --> 25:55.440
We agree on it, we rigidify it,

25:55.440 --> 25:59.280
and then we can all understand and connect and collect into it.

25:59.280 --> 26:01.600
So in the US, this is GPA, grade point average.

26:01.600 --> 26:03.120
If you get an A, that's a four.

26:03.120 --> 26:04.400
If you get a B, that's a three.

26:05.040 --> 26:08.640
Every student work can be pushed into a single spectrum

26:08.640 --> 26:10.160
that can be quickly averaged

26:10.160 --> 26:11.440
and get a grade point average.

26:12.240 --> 26:18.240
So Porter's insight is that data has been designed to travel.

26:18.240 --> 26:19.760
His term is that it's portable.

26:19.760 --> 26:21.760
It's been made to be portable.

26:21.760 --> 26:24.000
And the way it's made to be portable

26:24.000 --> 26:27.440
is it has context and subtlety stripped out.

26:28.400 --> 26:31.040
It's been designed to be understood across contexts.

26:31.760 --> 26:34.640
So I think the thing that Porter identifies for me

26:34.640 --> 26:36.720
is that the kind of what I would call

26:36.720 --> 26:39.360
the insensitivity and inhumanity of metrics

26:39.360 --> 26:40.800
is an essential design feature.

26:41.680 --> 26:44.320
In order to communicate readily at scale,

26:44.320 --> 26:46.800
we have to strip off things that require

26:46.800 --> 26:48.640
high context and nuance to understand.

26:49.600 --> 26:53.120
So the thing that makes metrics powerful,

26:53.120 --> 26:55.920
that is the quick aggregation, the easy comprehensibility,

26:56.000 --> 27:01.120
is achieved precisely at the cost of loss of nuance.

27:01.120 --> 27:02.800
And I'm not saying this is bad in every case.

27:02.800 --> 27:04.880
Like this is also, this is not just metrics.

27:04.880 --> 27:06.000
This is science, right?

27:06.000 --> 27:08.960
The reason why it's really easy to optimize

27:08.960 --> 27:11.440
for certain things like antibiotics

27:11.440 --> 27:13.680
is that having an antibiotic stop your infection

27:13.680 --> 27:15.680
is really easy for everyone to see.

27:15.680 --> 27:18.080
Having a lifesaving measure save on someone's life,

27:18.080 --> 27:19.360
that's easy to count.

27:19.360 --> 27:20.480
So those are the kinds of things

27:20.480 --> 27:22.720
that are very easy to collect large scale data for.

27:23.680 --> 27:27.040
Things that are highly variable require high sensitivity

27:27.040 --> 27:28.880
or that are subtle are very hard.

27:28.880 --> 27:31.360
And this is not saying they're not real, right?

27:31.920 --> 27:34.000
It's just saying that they're hard for everyone

27:34.000 --> 27:36.080
to assess quickly and easily.

27:36.880 --> 27:39.120
One of my favorite examples of here is like,

27:39.120 --> 27:43.120
so there are a lot of legal rights that we connect to age.

27:44.160 --> 27:47.120
And what we actually don't, we don't actually care about age.

27:47.120 --> 27:48.320
What we actually care about is intellectual

27:48.320 --> 27:52.480
and emotional maturity, but it would be a disaster

27:52.560 --> 27:55.440
if we granted voting rights based on intellectual

27:55.440 --> 27:56.480
and emotional maturity, right?

27:56.480 --> 27:58.080
You would need a particular judge.

27:58.080 --> 28:00.880
So there's a case where we make a trade-off

28:00.880 --> 28:03.280
and instead of exactly tracking the thing,

28:03.280 --> 28:05.920
we find a mechanical line in the U.S.

28:05.920 --> 28:07.760
You get to vote if you're 18, right?

28:08.480 --> 28:10.400
And that mechanical line is inarguable.

28:10.400 --> 28:12.320
Everyone assesses it at the same place.

28:12.320 --> 28:14.000
And that's a case where I think it's great.

28:14.000 --> 28:15.840
It is fantastic that for voting,

28:15.840 --> 28:18.240
we have a clear mechanical line that everyone can replicate.

28:19.120 --> 28:21.600
But for other things, like, I don't know,

28:21.600 --> 28:26.000
choosing your arts grants or choosing your fitness routine

28:26.000 --> 28:28.000
or choosing what your career is.

28:28.960 --> 28:32.480
These things, it's less important that our decision procedure

28:32.480 --> 28:35.920
and our targeting procedure are bound by the standard

28:35.920 --> 28:41.600
of absolute context-crossing decontextualization.

28:41.600 --> 28:45.520
I mean, the quick way to put it is that for Porter,

28:46.480 --> 28:52.080
data and therefore metrics are a designed engineer technology

28:52.080 --> 28:56.400
that gets us fast, portable aggregability

28:56.400 --> 28:57.520
at the cost of context.

28:58.400 --> 29:03.440
Yeah, so another thing that you talk about is the appeal of metrics.

29:03.440 --> 29:06.640
And I don't think it's just their tidiness.

29:06.640 --> 29:08.480
It's kind of the kind of authority

29:08.480 --> 29:10.000
that they seem to carry within them.

29:10.000 --> 29:13.280
You know, that's the final verdict on this issue.

29:13.360 --> 29:16.080
This such and such is five out of 10.

29:16.080 --> 29:18.800
That's it, you know, and so we're kind of,

29:18.800 --> 29:20.640
do you think we're less likely to challenge that

29:20.640 --> 29:23.600
because it seems like it is so black and white?

29:23.600 --> 29:27.760
Yeah, I mean, there are a lot of, this has been this puzzle for me

29:27.760 --> 29:30.480
for the longest time of why these things are so seductive.

29:31.120 --> 29:33.520
One of the early explanations I had was that

29:33.520 --> 29:35.760
there's this kind of like existential soothingness,

29:35.760 --> 29:39.520
like it's really painful to be exposed to the complexity of real values

29:39.520 --> 29:40.800
and this makes things easy.

29:40.800 --> 29:42.000
That's one explanation.

